[[Air Vice Marshal]] '''Sir Hazelton Robson Nicholl''' [[Order of the British Empire|KBE]] [[Order of the Bath|CB]] (14 January 1882 â€“ 14 August 1956) was a [[Royal Air Force]] officer who became Air Officer Commanding-in-Chief at [[RAF Middle East Command|Middle East Command]].

==RAF career==
Nicholl served as a private soldier in the London Scottish Volunteers in the [[Second Boer War]] and then transferred to the South Rhodesia Volunteers in 1903.<ref name=air>[http://www.rafweb.org/Biographies/Nicholl.htm Air of Authority - A History of RAF Organisation - Air Vice-Marshal Sir Hazelton Nicholl]</ref> He was [[Commissioned officer|commissioned]] into the [[Royal Flying Corps]] Special Reserve in 1915 during [[World War I]] and served as a pilot with [[No. 8 Squadron RAF|No. 8 Squadron]] before instructing at the [[Central Flying School]] and then becoming [[Officer Commanding]] [[No. 84 Squadron RAF|No. 84 Squadron]] and subsequently Officer Commanding [[No. 110 Squadron RAF|No. 110 Squadron]] on the [[Western Front (World War I)|Western Front]].<ref name=air/>

After the War he became a Staff Officer at the [[Air Ministry]] before being appointed Officer Commanding [[No. 70 Squadron RAF|No. 70 Squadron]] in 1926.<ref name=air/> He was made Deputy Director of Training and then Deputy Director of Personal Services before becoming Deputy Director of Manning at the Air Ministry in 1931.<ref name=air/> He went on to be Station Commander at [[RAF Calshot]] in 1932, Air Officer Commanding [[No. 23 Group RAF|No. 23 Group]] in 1933 and Air Officer Commanding Central Area in 1934.<ref name=air/> After that he was made a Member of the Air Board of the [[Royal Australian Air Force]] in 1935, Air Officer Commanding-in-Chief at [[RAF Middle East Command|Middle East Command]] in 1938 and Air Officer for Administration at Headquarters [[RAF Fighter Command|Fighter Command]] in 1939, the post he held in the early years of [[World War II]].<ref name=air/> He retired in 1942.<ref name=air/>

He retired to [[Scotland]] and became Controller of the [[RAF Benevolent Fund]].<ref>[http://www.flightglobal.com/pdfarchive/view/1956/1956%20-%201194.html Correspondence] Flight International, 31 August 1956</ref>

